name: Diethyl 3,4-dimethylthieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3904
Reason: 3,4-dimethylthieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate has a melting point influenced by functional groups relative to the base melting point of benzene, which is around 5°C. The basic unit for comparison can be the thieno[2,3-b]thiophene ring, which has a melting point around 106°C. The methyl groups (three in total) contribute to an increase in molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, with an approximate increase of +20°C per group, totaling +60°C. The carboxylate group introduces a polar carbonyl interaction, raising the melting point by approximately +40°C. The thienyl group introduces a rigid structure with potential hydrogen bonding, contributing approximately +30°C. The methyl group introduces a more asymmetric structure, reducing the crystal lattice stability, which might decrease the melting point by approximately -10°C. Summing up these changes: Thieno[2,3-b]thiophene base (+106°C), three methyl groups (+60°C), one carboxylate group (+40°C), and one methyl group (-10°C).
